TY  - JOUR
T1  - Do Stock Analysts Influence Merger Completion? An Examination of Postmerger Announcement Recommendations
AU  - Becher, David A.
AU  - Cohn, Jonathan B.
AU  - Juergens, Jennifer L.
Y1  - 2015/03/05
PY  - 2015
DA  - 2015/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2014.2065
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2014.2065
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 2430
EP  - 2448
VL  - 61
IS  - 10
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper investigates the effects of analyst recommendations issued after a merger announcement on deal completion. We find the probability of completion increases (decreases) with the favorability of acquirer (target) recommendations. Results from instrumental variables tests support causality running from recommendations to merger outcomes. Additional tests suggest that these relations are driven by target shareholders reassessing the merger offer in response to movements in acquirer and target valuations. We also find that favorably recommended firms in a proposed merger underperform following deal resolution, suggesting that investors overreact to postmerger announcement recommendations. This paper was accepted by Wei Jiang, finance.
AB  - This paper investigates the effects of analyst recommendations issued after a merger announcement on deal completion. We find the probability of completion increases (decreases) with the favorability of acquirer (target) recommendations. Results from instrumental variables tests support causality running from recommendations to merger outcomes. Additional tests suggest that these relations are driven by target shareholders reassessing the merger offer in response to movements in acquirer and target valuations. We also find that favorably recommended firms in a proposed merger underperform following deal resolution, suggesting that investors overreact to postmerger announcement recommendations. This paper was accepted by Wei Jiang, finance.
